ame rules as in 1845, which would invalidate modern voting methods and state laws. The dispute centers on the interpretation of Election Day statutes.\n  - id: 24-758, name: GEO Group, Inc. v. Menocal, description: The case is about whether a private contractor working for the government can be immune from a lawsuit when they follow instructions, similar to how government employees are protected.\n  - id: 24-1238, name: Montgomery v. Caribe Transport II, LLC, description: The Supreme Court is deciding whether a state law claim against a transportation broker can be preempted by federal law, which would prevent the claim from being pursued.\n  - id: 24-1046, name: Wolford v. Lopez, description: The case Wolford v. Lopez concerns whether Hawaii\'s law banning people from carrying firearms on private property open to the public without permission violates the Second Amendment right to publicly carry firearms, as established by the Supreme Court\'s decision in Bruen.\n  - id: 24-1234, name: United States v. Hemani, description: The case of United States v. Hemani, docket number 24-1234, concerns whether the government can temporarily disarm habitual marijuana users who continue to use the substance frequently. The issue revolves around a law that restricts Second Amendment rights for individuals who pose a perceived public safety risk due to their drug use.\n  - id: 22-58, name: United States v. Texas, description: The case centers on a dispute over the US government\'s immigration enforcement priorities, with the issue being whether states have standing to challenge federal policies and whether the government must apprehend and remove all non-citizens as required by law.\n  - id: 24-38, name: Little v. Hecox, description: The case Little v. Hecox concerns whether Idaho\'s law, which classifies athletes by sex rather than gender identity, unfairly discriminates against transgender males who identify as female and wish to compete in women\'s sports.\n  - id: 24-777, name: Urias-Orellana v. Bondi, Att\'y Gen., description: The case Urias-Orellana v. Bondi, Att\'y Gen., docket number 24-777, concerns the legal interpretation of whether undisputed facts qualify as persecution under a specific law.\n\nFollow these rules:\n- Extract parameters strictly according to the schema.\n- Apply the extraction instructions above.\n- Use context only when the user refers indirectly (e.g., "it", "that one").\n- If a parameter cannot be extracted, set it to null.\n- Return ONLY valid JSON. No commentary.\n\nReturn JSON in this format:\n{\n    "parameters": {\n        <param_name>: <value or null>\n    },\n    "reasoning": "<brief explanation>"\n}\n',)
